==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fadge
<hw>Fadge</hw> <pr>(f⟦acr⟧j)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OE.
<ets>faden</ets> to flatter, and AS. <ets>f⟦emac⟧gan</ets> to join,
unite, G. <ets>f⟦uum⟧gen</ets>, or AS. <ets>⟦amac⟧f⟦ae⟧gian</ets> to
depict; all perh. form the same root as E. <ets>fair</ets>. Cf.
<er>Fair</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, <er>Fay</er> to fit.]</ety> <def>To fit;
to suit; to agree.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They shall be made, spite of antipathy, to <qex>fadge</qex>
together.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Well, Sir, how <qex>fadges</qex> the new design ?</q>
<rj><qau>Wycherley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fadge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fadge
<hw>Fadge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etymol.
uncertain.]</ety> <def>A small flat loaf or thick cake; also, a
fagot.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fading</ent>⟦br⟧
